Cell Shape
2.5D X-Cell
Creates a 2.5D X structure per cell. 2.5D X-cell structures are used commonly in additive manufacturing and provide high directional stiffness.
Creates a simple cross structure per cell. Cross structures have good vertical and horizontal strength qualities.
Creates a structure based on selected geometry.
Creates a gyroid structure per cell. Gyroid structures have excellent isotropic strength properties and can be used effectively inside 3D prints.
2.5D Honeycomb
Creates a 2.5D Honeycomb structure per cell. 2.5D Honeycomb structures provide high directional stiffness and are easy to produce with a range of manufacturing methods.
Creates a Lidinoid structure per cell. Lidinoid structures have high surface areas and high stiffness which makes them effective for a range of applications.
Schwarz D
Creates a Schwarz D structure per cell. A structure which exhibits high stiffness properties and can be used effectively inside 3D printed parts.
Schwarz P
Creates a Schwarz P minimal structure surface per cell. The Schwarz P structure exhibits a high load bearing capacity due to the shape's inherent strain distribution.
Creates an X structure per cell. A widely used cell in a range of additive manufacturing processes for its self-supporting nature. Suitable for a range of applications including lightweighting.

Volumetric Modeling
Enables Volumetric Modeling tools.

The Gyroid shape can create stiff structures. However, can lead to trapped powder or resin in some printing processes. When using the Cross structure, consider using the Move/Rotate command to rotate the structure to ensure the Cross shape is able to support itself when printing.

Select a solid body or mesh body to lattice, then select a cell shape from the dropdown. Scale and position the structure using the manipulators. Then, specify the solidity of the structure using the fill percentage input, or select the Gradient Along Path to create a solidity gradient along a line. In the Offset tab, add a solidity offset region and specify its solidity.
Volumetric Lattice Information
Assigns an internal volumetric lattice structure to the selected body. A volumetric lattice must already be created in your design.
Also, you can only assign one volumetric lattice per component.

Modifies an existing solid body or mesh body by adding an internal lattice structure within the body boundary.

The mesh created with this tool can be extremely dense, consider using the Remesh tool in the Mesh workspace to make the model easier to work with. Also, the results can sometimes lead to small mesh shell artifacts. Consider using the Separate tool in the Mesh workspace to separate the small shells from the mesh body, then delete them.
